metadata.name: Plottable Era: (I) Primitive #305
metadata.description:
'Plottable Era: (I) Primitive' is the first generator in the "Era" generators series, highlighting different periods and civilizations. This first series "Primitive" shows the beginning of mankind with people exploring the mountains and traveling on the sea during sunset.

The digital version simulates ink effects and adds a subtle animation over the water. Each outcome is also physically plottable with pens: A SVG file can be exported (right-click save) to plot the piece physically. The plots are designed to be executed in A4 format on either fountain pens (on white paper) or gel pens (Black / Blue).

Thanks to the utility token decoupling, you can get a physical version: the digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their own materials and ship to collectors ‚Äì as long as NFT is owned at request time.

More details and Source code: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-era-primitive

@greweb ‚Äì 2022 ‚Äì tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM ‚Äì CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

reserve is set to previous 2022 physical plot collectors.

metadata.name: Pixel Management #909
metadata.description:
#tezpole has demonstrated to us all the importance of effective Cable Management. Intrigued by this challenge, I've delved deep into the pixels of this issue. üôÇ

Drawing inspiration from Rev Dan Catt‚Äôs 'Tally!' and applying similar principles of Cable Management, I've assembled a fun and free OE project.

This project dynamically evolves with each iteration.Grid is determined by a random value calculated as follows: the lower bound starts at 3 and increases incrementally with every 100 iterations, while the upper bound starts at 4 and increases with every 30 iterations. In practical terms, as the iteration count increases, both the minimum and maximum possible number of cols&rows gradually increase.

3200x3200px
Press [s] for .jpeg | Press [p] for .png
Made with p5.js

Rob Scalera | 2023

metadata.name: This is Not an Image #20
metadata.description:
When you see a piece of generative art, you are looking at a meta-message, an image whose value is not of form but of subtext. These images are a collision and reformation of ideas and conceptual histories between artists Nudoru and Sub Net. This dichotomy reminds us of the painting "The Treachery of Images" by Ren√© Magritte, where he paints a picture of a pipe but states underneath, "ceci n'est pas une pipe" (This is not a pipe), meaning that there is a schism between what a thing is and what it represents. What is unique about these works go beyond the images and text combinations themselves. It is about how images create new thoughts not by not pretending to be completely novel but that builds upon one another in a system of complex synthesis.

This token is part of the Floor Exhibit co-curated by the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC and Fort Gallery NFT.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press' p' to pause/resume.
Press' s' to save a screenshot. The image size is 2357‚Ää√ó‚Ää3000px.

objkt.name: Romeo and Juliet on Punched Cards (Free) #152

metadata.name: Romeo and Juliet on Punched Cards (Free) #152
metadata.description:
This artwork takes a modern approach to printing Shakespeare's classic play, Romeo and Juliet. The text is printed on old punched cards from an IBM machine from the 1970s, giving it a vintage look and feel. The lines of text are selected randomly from the play, creating a unique and dynamic representation of the story.

But there's a twist - the text on the punched cards is actually readable by the old machines, but it doesn't make sense to them. This highlights the stark contrast between the old and new technologies and how much has changed since the 1970s. Despite the advancements in technology, however, the beauty and significance of Romeo and Juliet remain timeless.

This artwork is a celebration of the past, present, and future, and the ways in which technology has evolved and continues to shape our lives.

Additionally, to ensure a fair distribution of the text from Romeo and Juliet, only 1024 tokens were selected at random. This allows for a diverse range of quotes and scenes to be included in the artwork, while still capturing the essence of the play as a whole. Whether you're a Shakespeare enthusiast or a tech-savvy individual, this artwork offers something for everyone to appreciate.

metadata.name: Reblend #52
metadata.description:
There are two creative features to this project.
The first feature is related to the production of colors at random points, so that geometric shapes are placed in proper harmony with each other and then allowed to process and produce colors at the intersection.
The second feature is the subtraction of a part of the shapes that are located in the center, and in the place of subtraction, geometric shapes are replaced, which will produce a new content of regular geometric shapes.
This innovative art not only challenges the traditional concepts of beauty but also encourages the thinking of viewers to combine colors and geometric shapes.

S = Save
Made by p5.js

metadata.name: Country Spirit I #253
metadata.description:
‚ÄúRaoul Pictor cherche son style‚Ä¶‚Äù (Raoul Pictor is looking for his style‚Ä¶) was launched in Saint-Gall, Switzerland, in 1993. It consists of a Mac LC computer, a 12-inch color screen, and an HP 500C printer.
The program presents an animation in which we can observe an artist, Raoul Pictor, working in his studio. He paints, paces while deep in thought, consults books from his library, plays the piano, and enjoys red wine. The sequence of these activities is non-linear. The canvas is seen from behind, resting on the easel in the center of the room. We are unable to see what is being painted. Once his painting is complete, he picks it up and exits through a side door. It is at this moment that the printer springs into action, delivering his unique, dated, and signed work.
This project has been exhibited in numerous exhibitions around the world. Subsequently, a Flash version, "Raoul Pictor Web Studio," was developed to make it available on the internet (2001). In 2013, for its 20th anniversary, an iOS version, "Raoul Pictor Mega Painter," was developed in collaboration with the great Matthieu Cherubini (mchrbn.net). 
In 2023, for its 30th anniversary, an update seemed necessary to continue the adventure on the fx(hash) platform ‚Äì thank you for making all of this possible! The development of this first fx version (‚ÄúCountry Spirit I‚Äù) was greatly enhanced by the wonderful support and expertise of the sha22.art team as well as our friends. Additional collections are now planned for the near future or special events...

[up_arrow], [space bar] : Painter jumps in first part of animation.

[p], [mouse click], [touch screen] : Save the painting when it is displayed.

metadata.name: <iframes> #110
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110

metadata.name: Tally! #1851
metadata.description:
Tally! Is a year long, free, open edition to celebrate fxhash v2. Data from the minting of Tally! will be used to create other new artworks.

This artwork is simply about counting up from one to wherever we end up, with a litle bit of Fizz Buzz thrown in. Mints that have a prime numbers* as factors will have slight variations. Sometimes those variations will combine, sometimes you have to get to really high numbers for multiple prime numbers to combine.

Where the finally Tally! ends up who knows? But there's going to be a lot of tallying along the way, and it'll give you something to do while waiting between other mints.

INSTRUCTIONS ::

'?forceWidth=xxxx' on the end of the URL to change the width of the image
's' = save image

metadata.name: Element #210
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

metadata.name: Action; System #6
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of Fran√ßois Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl

metadata.name: Nanopanorama #49
metadata.description:
Distorted noise with weird textures and funky shapes rendered using my rayhatcher algorithm.

4671 characters of pure Javascript, no libraries.

Some options can be changed via the URL:

&lw=.25 : The linewidth in millimetres.
&d=.4 : Line density (multiplier to linewidth).
&h=235 : Page height in millimetres. The aspect ratio is 16:9, for a width of 420mm, suitable for A3 plotting.
&bg=1 : Set to 0 to remove background rectangle (recommended for plotting).

When plotting, it is recommended to use a path reordering / optimizing tool such as axicli or vpype to greatly reduce the plotting time.

metadata.name: White Mountain Winter #22
metadata.description:
White Mountain Winter is collaboration between myself and the machine to describe scenes that are real, or were. Yet perhaps now foreign, or out of time, or far away. I provide the seed of a dream I remember, and trust the machine to help make it real again.

I grew up in a town much like some of these, homes dispersed throughout the valley beneath the shadows of the mountains rising around. This is a tribute to the memory of wintertime in that place; bleak, cold, grey, with the light seemingly always fading. Yet at the same time, the feeling of calm, solace, peace resonating through. Exposed to the mountain elements, yet protected by them. A delicate arrangement, but essential.

The seed of magic I remember is present in the experience of falling snow at dusk. Large flakes tumbling down and blanketing everything, no end in sight. The most striking thing is the silence. The fallen snow absorbing all distraction, insisting that your focus be sharpened to a singularity; right there, right then.

---
- Best rendered in Chrome browser (best performance, & canvas blur - please be patient :)
- Made with p5js
- Press "s" to save png
